## Section 2: Product Type

### Draft A: Interactive Web-Based Prompt Guide with Companion Resources

**LLM-Powered Self-Learning Prompt Guide (Primary) + Downloadable Tip Sheets (Companion)**

This product would be a web-hosted prompt guide—a curated library of pre-written, copy-and-paste prompts that child welfare supervisors and workers use with any publicly available LLM chat interface (such as ChatGPT, Claude, or Gemini) to explore how technology transitions will affect their roles, workflows, and teams. Each prompt module would follow the CRIT framework (Context, Role, Interview, Task), developed by Geoff Woods, which structures the interaction so that the user provides their situation (Context), the LLM is assigned a specific expert persona such as a change management specialist or public sector technology advisor (Role), the LLM asks the user clarifying questions before producing output (Interview), and the desired deliverable is clearly defined (Task). Users would customize each prompt by inserting details about their specific situation—the technology being adopted, their agency's timeline, their concerns—while the resource provides clear instructions on what to share and what not to share with an LLM.

The webpage would be organized into sections that mirror the phases of a technology transition:

- **Before the Decision:** Understanding what questions to ask about how a new system will change your work
- **During Implementation:** Preparing yourself and your team for workflow changes, new expectations, and shifting dynamics
- **After Go-Live:** Sustaining effective practice, identifying workarounds that signal deeper problems, and advocating for adjustments

Each section would contain two to four ready-to-use prompts, a brief plain-language explanation of the change management concept behind the prompt, and a "What to Expect" note describing the type of conversation the LLM will initiate. The guide would open with a foundational section titled **"Using AI Safely and Responsibly in Child Welfare"** that teaches users the basics of LLM interaction and, critically, how to participate in AI-assisted learning without disclosing personally identifiable information (PII), case details, or protected data. This section would include specific examples of safe vs. unsafe information sharing, written for an audience that may never have used an LLM before.

Before engaging with any CRIT prompt, users would paste a brief **primer prompt** into a new LLM conversation. The primer loads the key research frameworks—lead and lag measures, organizational culture and climate, ADKAR, implementation stages, systems thinking, and sociotechnical design—into the LLM's working memory so that all subsequent responses are grounded in the curated knowledge base rather than the LLM's generic training. For users whose tools do not maintain context across messages, the guide would also provide combined single-prompt versions that merge the primer content directly into each CRIT prompt. This three-layer architecture (webpage for the user → primer for the LLM → CRIT prompts for the conversation) ensures consistent, research-anchored guidance regardless of platform or user skill level.

Companion downloadable resources would include a one-page "Quick Reference: The CRIT Method" card, a printable "Questions to Bring to Your Supervisor" worksheet generated from prompt outputs, and a team discussion guide for use in staff meetings.

This format is distinctive because the product is not the content the user reads—it is the personalized conversation the user has. The prompt guide is the starting point; the LLM does the heavy lifting of tailoring the learning to each user's specific context. This makes the resource infinitely scalable, personally relevant, and usable across any jurisdiction regardless of the specific technology being adopted.

### Draft B: Multi-Format Learning Suite Anchored by an LLM Prompt Guide

**LLM Prompt Guide (Core) + Micro-Learning Modules (Scaffolding) + Self-Assessment Tool (Entry Point)**

This product suite would use three complementary formats, each serving a different function in the learning experience:

**1. Transition Readiness Pulse Check (Entry Point):** A brief, interactive web-based self-assessment (5–10 minutes) that supervisors can use with their teams to gauge preparedness for a technology transition. The assessment would surface areas of concern—such as unclear role changes, insufficient training plans, or unaddressed workflow gaps—and direct users to the relevant prompt modules. This provides a structured on-ramp for users who may not know where to start.

**2. LLM Prompt Guide (Core Learning Experience):** A curated set of four to six prompt modules, each built on the CRIT framework and designed to be copied into any LLM chat interface. Each module focuses on a specific dimension of technology transitions in child welfare: understanding how new systems change daily workflows, preparing for shifts in role expectations, recognizing organizational culture strain, communicating concerns upward effectively, and sustaining gains after go-live. Because the CRIT framework instructs the LLM to interview the user before generating output, each conversation is automatically personalized to the user's agency, role, and situation—without requiring a sophisticated AI user. Before using any CRIT prompt, users would paste a brief **primer prompt** that loads the resource's key research frameworks (lead and lag measures, organizational culture and climate, ADKAR, implementation stages, systems thinking, sociotechnical design) into the LLM's working memory. This ensures all responses draw on the same vetted knowledge base rather than the LLM's generic training data. A combined single-prompt fallback would also be available for users who prefer a one-step approach.

**3. Concept Primers (Scaffolding):** Short, plain-language web pages (500–800 words each) that introduce the change management or implementation science concept behind each prompt module. These primers ensure that users who have never encountered terms like "organizational readiness" or "implementation drivers" have enough background to engage meaningfully with the LLM conversation. Each primer ends with the prompt to copy and paste, creating a seamless transition from reading to doing.

The entire suite would open with a **"Getting Started with AI: A Guide for Child Welfare Professionals"** section covering what an LLM is and is not, how to access free LLM tools, step-by-step instructions for copying and pasting a prompt, a clear privacy and data safety protocol explaining what information is safe to share (role titles, general agency characteristics, timeline phases) and what must never be entered (names, case numbers, family details, system credentials), and tips for evaluating LLM output critically.

This multi-format approach accommodates different learning styles and comfort levels with technology. A supervisor who is confident with AI can skip straight to the prompts. A worker who has never used an LLM can start with the self-assessment, read a primer, and then try their first prompt with scaffolded support.

