## Section 3: Objective (200-Word Maximum)

### Draft A

Child welfare agencies across the country are acquiring new technology systems at an accelerating pace, yet research shows that the majority of public sector IT projects fail to meet their goals—and the root causes are more often organizational than technical. Frontline supervisors and workers, the people most directly affected by these transitions, are frequently the last to be meaningfully engaged in the process.

This resource will equip frontline child welfare staff and their supervisors to understand, prepare for, and actively shape technology transitions in their agencies. Built as an LLM-powered prompt guide using the CRIT framework (Context, Role, Interview, Task), it enables self-paced, personalized learning through any publicly available AI chat tool. Users copy pre-written prompts, customize them with details about their own situation, and receive tailored guidance grounded in change management, implementation science, and organizational behavior research. A foundational module on responsible AI use ensures that child welfare professionals can engage with LLMs without compromising client privacy or protected data. By putting research-backed frameworks directly into the hands of frontline staff—in a format that meets them where they are—this resource bridges the gap between organizational strategy and daily practice.

*(168 words)*

### Draft B

When a child welfare agency adopts new technology, the impact extends far beyond the screen. Workflows shift, roles evolve, supervisory relationships are tested, and organizational culture is strained in ways that are often unanticipated. For frontline workers and supervisors—who must continue serving families through the disruption—these transitions can feel imposed rather than supported.

This resource provides a new kind of learning experience: a web-based prompt guide that enables child welfare professionals to use any LLM chat tool as a personalized change management coach. Each prompt follows the CRIT framework, which instructs the AI to interview the user about their specific context before generating guidance. The result is tailored, actionable support that adapts to any jurisdiction, any technology, and any role. Companion resources—including a readiness self-assessment, plain-language concept primers, and downloadable team discussion tools—scaffold the experience for users who may be encountering both change management concepts and AI tools for the first time. A dedicated privacy and data safety module ensures responsible use. By centering the frontline perspective and leveraging AI as a learning tool, this resource addresses a critical gap in the child welfare technology TA landscape.

*(177 words)*

