## Section 4: Justification

### 4a. Connection to Children's Bureau and ACF Priorities

#### Draft A

This resource directly supports several current Children's Bureau and ACF priorities. ACF has identified CCWIS modernization as a central strategy for improving child safety, permanency, and well-being outcomes. The recently launched Child Welfare Technology Incubator provides states with technical assistance across the CCWIS lifecycle, including governance, stakeholder alignment, and readiness support. ACF's partnership with Iowa to develop the VISION system—positioned as a national model for CCWIS modernization—explicitly emphasizes user-centered design and freeing caseworkers from outdated systems so they can focus on children and families. The ACF issue brief *Modernizing Child Welfare Technologies and Tools* (Inman & Adams, 2026) underscores that current systems often operate as "digital filing cabinets" and that modernization must help caseworkers make timely, accurate decisions.

However, existing federal technical assistance resources focus primarily on governance, data quality, and system architecture. There is comparatively little guidance designed *for* frontline workers and supervisors about how to navigate the organizational disruption that accompanies these transitions. This resource fills that gap by operationalizing ACF's stated commitment to user-centered systems—not just in how technology is designed, but in how it is introduced, adopted, and sustained by the workforce.

The product format also advances a broader federal priority. The U.S. Department of Labor's AI Literacy Framework (TEN 07-25, February 2026) identifies hands-on, experiential AI learning as the most effective approach to workforce AI literacy, and calls for programs that teach responsible AI use including data protection and ethical boundaries. The OECD's 2026 policy brief on building an AI-ready public workforce similarly recommends blended approaches that combine scalable tools with context-specific learning. By embedding AI literacy directly into the learning experience—teaching child welfare professionals to use LLMs responsibly while simultaneously building change management knowledge—this resource delivers dual value: it strengthens the workforce's capacity to navigate technology transitions and builds foundational AI skills that will serve them across their careers.

Additionally, ACF's "A Home for Every Child" initiative depends on a stable, effective workforce. Research by Glisson and colleagues demonstrates that organizational culture and climate directly affect caseworker turnover, service quality, and youth outcomes in child welfare. Poorly managed technology transitions exacerbate workforce stress and disengagement at precisely the moment agencies can least afford it. This resource supports workforce stability by equipping staff to navigate change constructively.

#### Draft B

ACF has made child welfare technology modernization a top priority, linking it directly to the Executive Order on Fostering the Future for American Children and Families and the "A Home for Every Child" initiative. The Child Welfare Technology Incubator, launched alongside the Iowa VISION partnership in February 2026, signals a major federal investment in helping states plan, implement, and sustain modern CCWIS systems. ACF Assistant Secretary Alex Adams has stated that strong technology, data, and analytics infrastructure is essential for making decisions that center the best interests of children and families.

This resource aligns with these priorities by addressing the workforce dimension of technology modernization—a dimension that ACF has consistently identified as critical but that remains underserved in the current TA landscape. The Capacity Building Center for States has produced valuable guidance on change and implementation (including the tip sheet *Mapping Change and Implementation to CCWIS Projects*), but these resources are designed primarily for project teams and agency leadership. The proposed resource complements this work by extending change management support to the frontline workforce—the caseworkers and supervisors whose daily adoption of new systems determines whether a technology investment succeeds or fails.

The LLM-powered prompt guide format is particularly well-suited to the current federal policy environment. New York State's 2026 AI training pilot demonstrated that even among state employees with zero prior AI experience, structured hands-on programs produced a 36% increase in confidence with generative AI tools. The DOL's 2026 AI Literacy Framework emphasizes that AI literacy is "most effectively developed through direct, hands-on use" and that workers must learn to protect sensitive data while maintaining accountability for outcomes. This resource models that principle: users learn change management content *through* responsible AI use, building two critical competencies simultaneously.

This resource also connects to ACF's emphasis on data-informed decision-making and the CFSR process. Technology transitions that are poorly managed produce poor data quality, low system utilization, and workaround behaviors that undermine the very outcomes these investments are meant to improve. By helping frontline staff understand and engage with technology transitions, this resource supports the data quality and practice improvements that ACF's performance accountability framework depends upon.

### 4b. Does a Similar Product Exist Elsewhere?

#### Draft A

Several related resources exist, but none occupy the specific niche this product would fill—and none use an LLM-powered, prompt-based learning format.

The Capacity Building Center for States has produced the *Change and Implementation in Practice* series, which provides valuable guidance on implementation science concepts for child welfare. The Center also developed the tip sheet *Mapping Change and Implementation to CCWIS Projects* (2020), which offers questions for CCWIS teams organized around implementation topics. These resources are sound, but they are designed for implementation teams and agency leaders—not for frontline workers and supervisors as a primary audience. They are also static documents that provide the same content regardless of the user's specific context.

The National Child Welfare Workforce Institute (NCWWI) has produced resources on organizational culture and climate, including reference lists and workforce studies, but these focus on organizational assessment rather than practical guidance for navigating specific technology transitions.

The Child Welfare Technology Incubator launched by ACF in 2026 provides strategic advisory, readiness support, and risk scanning—all targeted at state-level CCWIS project teams.

Outside child welfare, the CRIT framework (Woods, 2024) has been applied in corporate, legal, and sales contexts, but has not been adapted for public sector human services. Similarly, the Prosci ADKAR model and Kotter's 8-Step framework are widely used for technology change management but have not been translated into practical, frontline-accessible tools for child welfare workers.

No existing resource combines three elements simultaneously: (1) change management and implementation science content tailored to child welfare technology transitions, (2) a frontline-worker audience, and (3) an LLM-powered, personalized learning format. This product would be the first to do so.

#### Draft B

A landscape scan reveals several adjacent resources but no direct equivalent—either in content focus or product format.

The most closely related content product is the Capacity Building Center for States' *Mapping Change and Implementation to CCWIS Projects* (2020), a one-page tip sheet with conversation starters organized around implementation topics. This is useful for project teams but is brief by design, static in format, and does not provide the depth of guidance, scenario-based learning, or personalization that the proposed resource would offer.

The most closely related format precedent is outside child welfare entirely. New York State's AI training pilot (2026) provided 1,200+ state employees with structured AI training and a secure generative AI tool, producing measurable skill gains. The DOL's AI Literacy Framework (2026) calls for experiential, hands-on AI learning integrated with job-specific contexts. However, no similar program exists in child welfare, and none are designed as self-service prompt guides that users can access independently through any LLM.

Outside the public sector, Geoff Woods' CRIT framework has been applied to business strategy, legal marketing, and sales enablement. The CRIT Prompt Builder (prompt-building.lovable.app) offers a generic tool for constructing CRIT prompts, but it is not domain-specific and does not include the subject-matter expertise, privacy guidance, or contextual scaffolding that child welfare professionals would need.

This resource would be the first to synthesize cross-domain insights from change management, implementation science, organizational behavior, and systems thinking into an LLM-powered prompt guide specifically designed for child welfare frontline staff navigating technology transitions—while simultaneously building foundational AI literacy skills in a workforce that largely lacks them.

